ODE X. To LICINIUS.

F thou wouldst live secure and free, Thou wilt not keep far out at sea Licinius, evermore3 Nor, fearful of the gales that sweep The ocean wide, too closely creep Along the treacherous shore.

The man, who, with a soul serene, Doth cultivate the golden mean, Escapes alike from all The squalor of a sordid cot, And from the jealousies begot By wealth in lordly hall.

The mighty pine is ever most By wild winds swayed about and tossed, With most disastrous crash Fau high-topped towers‚ and ever, where The mountains' summit points in air, Do bolted lightnings flash.
